{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17586062","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17586062"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:24:58+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:24:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15053"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15053","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15053"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.07,0.15,0.74,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7741"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109936"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7741","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7741"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15053"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92294"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1170"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8115"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18904"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18906"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109936","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109936"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ERhabdomyolysis is a condition characterised by skeletal muscle breakdown leading to release of myoglobin and other cellular contents into the bloodstream.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the key management principles for rhabdomyolysis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Restrict fluids and maintain urine acidification","Give minimal fluids with mandatory urine alkalinisation","Give aggressive fluids and always alkalinise urine","Give aggressive fluids with selective urine alkalinisation and dialysis if indicated","Give aggressive fluids and avoid urine alkalinisation"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct management approach for rhabdomyolysis includes \u003Cstrong\u003Egiving aggressive fluids with selective urine alkalinisation and dialysis if indicated\u003C/strong\u003E. Aggressive fluid resuscitation is essential to maintain renal perfusion and prevent acute kidney injury from myoglobin precipitation in renal tubules. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERestricting fluids and maintaining urine acidification\u003C/strong\u003E would be harmful as it would increase the risk of acute kidney injury. Myoglobin is more likely to precipitate in acidic urine, and inadequate hydration would fail to dilute and clear myoglobin from the renal tubules.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGiving minimal fluids with mandatory urine alkalinisation\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect because volume expansion is the cornerstone of management. Without adequate fluid resuscitation, alkalinisation alone is insufficient to prevent renal damage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGiving aggressive fluids and always alkalinising urine\u003C/strong\u003E is not the best approach because alkalinisation is not universally recommended. While it may help prevent myoglobin precipitation, it should be considered selectively based on the clinical scenario and is not mandatory in all cases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGiving aggressive fluids and avoiding urine alkalinisation\u003C/strong\u003E misses the potential benefit of alkalinisation in selected cases. While aggressive fluid administration is the primary intervention, alkalinisation may be beneficial in severe cases with high risk of acute kidney injury.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDialysis should be initiated based on standard clinical indications such as refractory hyperkalaemia, severe acidosis, uraemia, or volume overload that does not respond to conventional therapy. There is no specific creatine kinase or myoglobin level that mandates dialysis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Aggressive fluid administration is essential in rhabdomyolysis to prevent acute kidney injury and maintain urine output","Urinary alkalinisation should be considered on a case-by-case basis in rhabdomyolysis","Dialysis decisions in rhabdomyolysis should be based on standard clinical indications including hyperkalaemia, acidosis and volume status"],"references":["Parekh R, Care DA, Tainter CR. Rhabdomyolysis: advances in diagnosis and treatment. Emerg Med Pract. 2012 Mar;14(3):1-15; quiz 15. PMID: 22497086.","Chavez, L.O., Leon, M., Einav, S. et al. Beyond muscle destruction: a systematic review of rhabdomyolysis for clinical practice. Crit Care 20, 135 (2016). https://doi.org/10.1186/s13054-016-1314-5","Jennette, J. C., \u0026 D\u0027Agati, V. D. (2023). Heptinstall\u0027s Pathology of the Kidney. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science","Koeppen, B. M., \u0026 Stanton, B. A. (2018). Renal Physiology E-Book: Renal Physiology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92294"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15053"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92294","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92294"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-27T17:10:42+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-27T17:10:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7741"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":